					<div class="commentheading">On November 01, 2007 at 11:54 PM, Donna (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Toffee</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">I've been making toffee for 15 years, and I've never had a problem with it separating... I use a heavy All-Clad sauce pan, and add all my ingredients at the beginning on low-medium heat (butter, sugar, water, corn syrup).  <br />
<br />
Over the course of the years, I've found that it takes me a good half hour to make a batch of toffee.  It cannot be rushed, and I have a special wooden soon that I use to constantly stir and incorporate the ingredients.  It looks very much like a regular wooden spoon, but the tip is flattened, so's I can get into the corner of the saucepan.  I wet down the interior sides of the pan, so it cooks evenly.  <br />
<br />
Usually after it hits 270, there's a tiny window where it finishes up at 290-- it goes wicked fast, so I watch it like a hawk.</div>
